<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="293" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,295,646]" pageId="3" pageNumber="293">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,299,295,321]" pageId="3" pageNumber="293">Description:</emphasis>
Body length 
<quantity box="[456,579,295,322]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="293" unit="mm" value="11.0" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="10.0">10–12 mm</quantity>
(number = 8). Body color light yellow to white, without dark pattern (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1752,1776]" captionTargetBox="[188,1400,741,1729]" captionTargetId="figure-240@2.[188,1400,741,1729]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Rhopalopsole GR, nymph habitus, dorsal and ventral views. A: smaller nymph; B: larger nymph." pageId="3" pageNumber="293">Fig. 2A–B</figureCitation>
); body smooth on surface, bearing sparse, short setae. Triocellate; compound eyes reduced into small spots, with length only three times that of the ocellus (
<figureCitation box="[673,795,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1217,1241]" captionTargetBox="[151,1396,669,1193]" captionTargetId="figure-181@3.[151,1435,669,1193]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Rhopalopsole GR, nymphs. A: head, dorsal; B: head, ventral; C: mandible; D: lacinia; E: labium." pageId="3" pageNumber="293">Fig. 3A–B</figureCitation>
). Mouthparts mostly sclerotized. Lacinia short, inner edge on apex divided into 3 large teeth, followed by a row of hair brushes. Glossae slightly shorter than the paraglossae (
<figureCitation box="[159,281,439,465]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1217,1241]" captionTargetBox="[151,1396,669,1193]" captionTargetId="figure-181@3.[151,1435,669,1193]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Rhopalopsole GR, nymphs. A: head, dorsal; B: head, ventral; C: mandible; D: lacinia; E: labium." pageId="3" pageNumber="293">Fig. 3C–E</figureCitation>
). Pronotum rectangular, typical of this family. Mesothorax and metathorax are weakly sclerotized, but the wing pads and complex ventral sclerites are still obvious in the HDR (High Dynamic Range) images (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1862,1886]" captionTargetBox="[151,1332,1266,1838]" captionTargetId="figure-201@3.[151,1435,1266,1838]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 4. Rhopalopsole GR, nymphal thorax. A–B: dorsal mesothorax and metathorax, scanned figure and outline of wing pads; C–D: ventral prothorax and mesothorax, scanned figure and outline of the thoracic sclerites." pageId="3" pageNumber="293">Fig. 4A– D</figureCitation>
). The results of morphological study showed that these features, especially the mouthparts and thoracic sclerites, match those of the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[437,591,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Leuctridae" genus="Rhopalopsole" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="293" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[437,591,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="293">Rhopalopsole</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
